## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Critical Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET Core+. This is the primary blocker.
2. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` is also removed** — no-op/throws.
3. The idiomatic replacement is **`CancellationToken` + `Task`**.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Will throw OperationCanceledException if timeout fires
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    // Async-native overload (preferred)
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Cancellation is cooperative** | Unlike `Thread.Abort()`, the `CancellationToken` only works if `work` checks it. CPU-bound loops must call `ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` periodically. |
| **Uncancellable work keeps running** | If `work` ignores the token, the task runs to completion in the background even after you throw `TimeoutException`. This is a fundamental behavior change. |
| **`default(T)` semantics changed** | For `struct` types, `default` already worked the same, but the old code's `result = default` was a race condition — the new code avoids it entirely. |
| **Exception wrapping differs** | Old code wrapped in `AggregateException`; `Task.Run` does too, but `GetAwaiter().GetResult()` unwraps it automatically to the original exception. Callers catching `AggregateException` will break. |

### Caller Migration

```csharp
// BEFORE (.NET Framework)
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => SomeExpensiveWork(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// AFTER (.NET 8) — work must accept and respect the token
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct =>
    {
        // Check cancellation in loops / between steps
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        return SomeExpensiveWork(ct);
    },
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### If You Truly Need Hard Abort (last resort)

For wrapping legacy code that can't be made cancellation-aware, you can run it in a **separate process** — the only safe hard-kill mechanism left in .NET 8. In-process `Thread.Abort` has no equivalent and is intentionally gone.
